During the period 1994-2009, she tracked more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer with her colleagues in Britain, but also 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the display finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men the same likelihood of prostate cancer, as for 19 percent of those whose ring and display fingers were equal.
However, in men whose finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk declined by 33 percent, in men to sixty by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which already form in prenatal age, evidently reflects the different levels of gender hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer display finger.
Previous research found that just testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
