On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany adopts a fundamentally new perspective of designing our future, which conflicts with maintaining the old traditions of a majority of its partners.
In view of the resistances in Europe, we begin to speculate in Germany over three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the re-introduction of the German Mark - although this sounds more like science fiction at the moment - is supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
Third parties: a reshaping of the euro according to German proposals, which means more macroeconomic control; strict fiscal management; punishment of the countries that overcome the requirements; more possiblely, the setting of payments of some countries and the expansion of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position has been clear and has been distinguished for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission gained incentives for deficits and the German government moved out of a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the difference between what Germany felt necessary (strength tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign laid the Middle-European country as Merkel painfully left the decision to rescue Greece.
This was criticized at the time, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and public opinion were absolutely against Greece's rescue.
Lastly, Merkel comes out again in the last October days with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union agreements in order to enable the rescue of a country, while at the same time committing private loanmakers to bear some of the costs.
This position was designed as an anti-European as it drives the Irish crisis and all the following.
But their proposal, although somewhat agreed, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will participate in the European Union reform, which is intended to enable these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to exceed it.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which the countries that are infringed can be harshly punished, forced to explain themselves incapable of payment, and in this case the private sector must take part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard growth rate, with high savings and investment rates, consumption moderation, improving productivity and competitiveness, and positive foreign balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the payment balance, as listed by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly to not understand it.
It is not just about dropping the state deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope the current turbulence will go more quietly.
