US changes rules for receiving a visa
The persons must present themselves before their conversation at the consulate at the visa application service agencies; costs will be shortened.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedure for applying for a visa in the Embassy of the United States and in the consulates will be changed.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves before their discussion in the consulate at the visa application service agencies (ASC, the initial letters in English).
The ASC staff takes into account the biometric data of the applicant reviewed by the consulate prior to the discussion.
The new procedure has certain benefits for the aspirants, including:
The overall cost of the visa processing decreases, because it is no longer necessary to pay separately the date agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transportation service with which the document is delivered.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counterweight of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for time workers) and $390 for handlers and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to talk at the consulate; they only have to imagine at the nearest ASC where they submit their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, the applicants who need a second appointment for discussion in the consulate remain less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service supply.
Additional information on the new procedure for visa application can be found at the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
